{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/pulls/795","id":4084960319,"node_id":"PR_kwDOSbOoU87ze4w_","html_url":"https://github.com/link-assistant/formal-ai/pull/795","diff_url":"https://github.com/link-assistant/formal-ai/pull/795.diff","patch_url":"https://github.com/link-assistant/formal-ai/pull/795.patch","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/issues/795","number":795,"state":"closed","locked":false,"title":"Rank every purchase option cheapest-first over a constraint links network","user":{"login":"konard","id":1431904,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE0MzE5MDQ=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1431904?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard","html_url":"https://github.com/konard","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"body":"Closes #781.\n\nThe reported session failed with a bare `403 GET https://shopozz.ru/...` and stopped. The underlying gaps were larger than one blocked request: research stopped after a single search-and-fetch round, and there was no way to represent *what an answer has to satisfy*, so a compatibility question could only ever produce one recommendation rather than the options a buyer actually wants.\n\n## What is here\n\n**Option networks (`src/option_network.rs`).** A product-agnostic constraint/option engine. A network holds what the answer must supply, what each discovered candidate supplies, and every **minimal set** of candidates that jointly satisfies the requirement — so an option made of *two separate items* (a conversion adapter plus the part it adapts) is a first-class answer, not an afterthought. Options are listed **cheapest first**, with the provenance ladder (authentic → official-compatible → generic-compatible) only breaking ties. Arithmetic is fixed-point, so ranking is deterministic.\n\nIt is an associative links network rather than a scoring model: constraints and established facts are ordinary `world_model::Context` links, and the still-open part of a question is an ordinary `ContextDiff`. `links_notation()` projects the whole network, sources included.\n\nNothing in the module names a product domain. `the_same_engine_sources_a_subject_that_shares_no_vocabulary_with_the_issue` drives the identical engine with a darkroom enlarger lens mount and a m39→m42 conversion ring.\n\n**Reading evidence (`src/option_evidence.rs`).** Candidates and prices are read out of fetched page text. The constraints supply the units to look for — a constraint wanting `output_voltage` in `V` makes the page search for *a number followed by `V`* — so no attribute name is ever matched against prose and the same code reads a Russian spec sheet and an Indian listing. An attribute the page does not state is **left open** rather than guessed.\n\n**Deeper research.** The planner now deepens across rounds instead of stopping after one search and fetch, skipping sources already read.\n\n## Two things worth reviewing closely\n\n**The deepening trigger is deliberately conservative, and that is a considered trade.** Token coverage is a weak proxy for \"answered\", and how much of a question a page echoes varies by language — the same page shape leaves two aspects open in Hindi and none in English. My first rule (any proper subset of aspects open) regressed five tests by re-searching questions that were already answered. Deepening now requires **exactly one** open aspect of a question with at least three. The cost is that genuinely partial answers with two or more gaps are returned as-is; answering with what was found beats spending a round on a guess about what is missing.\n\n**A parsing bug this caught.** Acer's real part number `A13-045N2A` ends in `2A`, which read as a 2-ampere rating and made a genuine adapter look underpowered enough to drop out of the answer entirely. Numbers inside alphanumeric tokens are now not measurements — `a_digit_inside_a_part_number_is_not_read_as_a_measurement`.\n\n**An E2E check I added and then removed.** I asserted over the real transport that no source is fetched twice. It cannot work: the planner is stateless and re-derives from the transcript, so every traced request replays all prior tool calls and a repeated URL is indistinguishable from replayed history. The invariant is real but only observable at the planner level, where `a_source_already_read_is_not_read_again` covers it. The reasoning is recorded in the script so it does not get added back.\n\n## Testing\n\n- 24 unit tests across `issue_781`, `issue_781_option_network`, `issue_781_option_evidence`, including a whole-task test that assembles the complete option set from page text alone and asserts the cheapest answer is the two-item combination.\n- Full suite green locally: **1839 unit / 153 integration, 0 failures**. CI green on `030b63cf`.\n- Per-requirement trace in `docs/case-studies/issue-781/requirements.md` (R12–R20), each row naming the function and the test that evidences it.\n\nRegenerated the committed self-AST census, its Agent CLI session, and the self-healing case, and repointed the `looks_like_error` meta-function record: all are censuses of real source and went stale when `Progress` moved out of `planner.rs` into its own module to stay under the file-size gate.\n\n## Not done\n\nThe option network is exercised through its own tests and reads real page text, but it is **not yet wired into the agentic planner's answer path** — a live session does not yet return tiered, cheapest-first option lists. That wiring is the natural next step.\n","created_at":"2026-07-19T06:18:39Z","updated_at":"2026-07-19T14:23:04Z","closed_at":"2026-07-19T14:22:59Z","merged_at":"2026-07-19T14:22:59Z","merge_commit_sha":"eeecd44ea44fa8bcd3f57af7b2a49babc8d5dc5c","assignees":[{"login":"konard","id":1431904,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE0MzE5MDQ=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1431904?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard","html_url":"https://github.com/konard","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/konard/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false}],"requested_reviewers":[],"requested_teams":[],"labels":[],"milestone":null,"draft":false,"commits_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/pulls/795/commits","review_comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/pulls/795/comments","review_comment_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/pulls/comments{/number}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/issues/795/comments","statuses_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/link-assistant/formal-ai/statuses/030b63cfd2c5253653cea893bc048692825fe017","head":{"label":"link-assistant:issue-781-c52371d60a25","ref":"issue-781-c52371d60a25","sha":"030b63cfd2c525365